"type":"family_connection","display_label":"Father-in-law of Capt. Samuel Hart — grandfather of Emma Hart Willard's mother","related_id":"I00034","link_text":"Lydia Hinsdale Hart"},{"type":"family_connection","display_label":"Father-in-law of Capt. Samuel Hart — grandfather of Emma Hart Willard's mother","related_id":"H00597","link_text":"Emma Hart Willard"},{"type":"family_connection","display_label":"Father-in-law of Capt. Samuel Hart — grandfather of Emma Hart Willard's mother","related_id":"H00598","link_text":"Almira Hart Phelps"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Grandfather of Emma Hart Willard and Almira Phelps","body":"His daughter Lydia Hinsdale married Capt. Samuel Hart in 1770 — their daughters Emma Hart Willard founded Troy Female Seminary as a pioneer of women's education, and Almira Hart Lincoln Phelps wrote textbooks read by generations. Both granddaughters became among the most consequential 19th-century American educators."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Great-grandfather of the Learned Blacksmith","body":"His son Elijah Hinsdale was the grandfather of Elihu Burritt, the New Britain blacksmith who became internationally famous as 'the Learned Blacksmith' — a self-taught polyglot who founded the League of Universal Brotherhood. Burritt was thus first cousin once removed to Emma Hart Willard and Almira Phelps."},{"number":3,"category":"military","header":"Ensign to Captain in the Connecticut Trained Band","body":"He rose through the ranks of Connecticut's 6th Regiment, 15th Company — Ensign in 1749, Lieutenant in 1752, Captain in 1759. He was described as a man of rare military and literary ability."},{"number":4,"category":"career","header":"Blacksmith with a shop on Berlin Street","body":"He worked as a blacksmith from a shop near his house, opposite what would become the Methodist Church on Berlin Street, New Britain. In 1781 he bought the 70-acre Deacon Josiah Lee farm from John Richards."}],"military_service":[{"rank":"Captain","notes":"Captain of 15th Company, 6th Regiment, CT Militia."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Captain John Hinsdale","title":"Captain","first_name":"John","last_name":"Hinsdale","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"slug":"john-hinsdale-1706"},"X00040":{"id":"X00040","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{},"death":{},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00039","children_ids":["I00034","X01931"],"marriage_number":1}],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 281"}],"gender":"female","tags":[],"number_of_marriages":1,"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Elizabeth Cole Hinsdale","first_name":"Elizabeth","last_name":"Hinsdale","married_names":["Hinsdale"],"maiden_name":"Cole"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"elizabeth-cole"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}